  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Exploring Interface Options**\n\nI\'m now investigating available styles and assets, considering whether to build an interactive interface from scratch. My focus is on designing a high-quality classroom center. I\'m aiming for an elegant login screen mirroring \"Classe de Mr Lejoly,\" but optimized and with an appealing sketch, of course.\n\n\n**Refining Aesthetic Details**\n\nI\'m now diving deeper into the aesthetic. I\'ve decided we can create those hand-drawn elements with Tailwind and SVG for icon details and CSS for frames. The goal is a soft sky-blue playful border with children\'s drawings. I\'m focusing on \"Bienvenue dans ta classe!\" in a playful handwritten style, \"Classe de Mr Lejoly\" with a prominent gray handwritten font (maybe Fredoka or Comic Sans Neue), and a clean subtitle.\n\n\n**Designing Interactive Elements**\n\nI\'m now focusing on interactive elements, specifically the login screen\'s \"Se connecter\" button. I\'m exploring an interactive design where clicking reveals a student list. Alternatively, a name input field and \"C\'est parti !\" button is another option. I envision a beautiful \"connected\" second screen.\n\n\n**Defining Subject Choices**\n\nI\'m now designing the subject selection interface, envisioning a 2x2 grid with visually appealing cards. I\'m prioritizing elegance. I\'m leaning toward Lucide-React icons embedded in structured vector containers, for a crisp, professional, yet friendly aesthetic for the **Fran\303\247ais** card. I\'m focusing on a modern design for a 10-12 year old, which should be clean with no babyish designs. I\'m aiming for pastel background colors and solid branding colors, elegant and perfectly proportional.\n\n\n**Implementing Font and Style**\n\nI\'m now integrating custom Google Fonts, such as Fredoka, Caveat, Architects Daughter, and Sora, into the design via `src/index.css`. The goal is to perfectly replicate the premium look and feel of the teacher\'s screenshots. I am now working on the card designs, focusing on a clean, professional aesthetic.\n\n\n**Expanding Interactive Categories**\n\nI\'m now expanding the subject selection screen\'s cards into interactive modules to enhance engagement. \"Jeux\" will feature interactive elements using Lucide icons. I\'m focusing on \"D\303\251fis, quiz et jeux \303\251ducatifs...\" for that card. The \"Histoire, g\303\251ographie, sciences...\" card will be `FlaskConical` in a clean layout. I\'m prioritizing minimal, modern icons for these 5th and 6th-grade students, adapting the colors and style of the site and the interactive experience of each section in a way that is tailored to their curriculum (5e/6e primaire in French-speaking Belgium). I aim to create mini-activities or custom interactive mini-modules.\n\n\n**Developing Interactive Modules**\n\nI\'m now deep-diving into the interactive modules for each subject. For Fran\303\247ais, I\'m brainstorming mini-games like \"Le Conjugueur Magique\" or \"Le D\303\251fi d\'Orthographe.\" Math\303\251matiques will focus on a mental math game, like \"D\303\251fi de Calcul Mental,\" with a retro-modern scoreboard. I\'m imagining a fast-paced keypress/click challenge. \303\211veil will feature \"L\'Explorateur d\'\303\211veil,\" an interactive map or multiple-choice quiz covering geography, science, and history. Lastly, Jeux will include \"Le Pendu R\303\251invent\303\251\" or a Sudoku solver.\n\n\n**Integrating Math Activities**\n\nI\'m now integrating an engaging math puzzle, thinking specifically of a \"Target Number\" game to keep students\' minds sharp. This will significantly elevate the platform\'s functionality and premium feel, creating a fully interactive tool the teacher can readily use with students. I\'m excited about how blown away they\'ll be that this application works, in addition to being fully functional. I\'m taking a look at `src/index.css` to manage Google Fonts. I am looking into importing \"Architects Daughter\", \"Caveat\", \"Fredoka\", \"Quicksand\", and \"Inter\" for their various aesthetic benefits. I confirmed Google Fonts can be imported using `@import url(...)` at the top of the file, and then styling using utility values.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 16
      nanos: 300195590
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
